# Agent context

Read **`AGENTS.md`** for repo map, product rules (subscription vs purchase access), conventions, and the append-only **Agent memory log**.

If instructions conflict, prefer the codebase and **`AGENTS.md`**, then the current user message.

**`docs/submission.md`** and **`AGENTS.md`** are **tracked in git**. When a change affects product, access rules, or API behavior, update **`docs/api-contract.md`** in the same change batch and add or extend **`docs/submission.md`** / **`AGENTS.md`** as appropriate so the PR contains the full story.

## Product rules to preserve

- **Subscription** grants access to **all books** while active.
- **Non-subscribed** users can only access books they **purchased**.
- The API should make locked vs accessible clear to the frontend (e.g. `is_accessible`, `access_reason`).
- Purchase endpoints should be **idempotent** for already-owned books.

## Architecture expectations

- Keep controllers thin; business rules in services; access control centralized and reused.
- Validate inputs; return consistent error shapes and correct HTTP codes.

## API contract (`docs/api-contract.md`)

**Scope**: browser integration only (URLs, JSON, auth, errors). Operator/env detail stays in **README**.

Whenever you change **routes, request/response JSON, status codes, auth behavior, CORS, JWT claims, or any frontend-visible API behavior**, update **`docs/api-contract.md`** in the **same change series** as the code.

## Repo map (`AGENTS.md`)

The repo map must be **non-speculative**. When you add top-level structure, update **`AGENTS.md`** and append **one line** to the **Agent memory log** in the same change series.

## No assistant attribution in git metadata

Do not add tool or assistant attribution to PR titles, PR bodies, or commit messages.
